text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeArticle:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingComment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!Production and Understanding%0a%0a:Author: NickG%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe relationship between being able to convey one's thoughts in a certain language versus being able to understand someone else in that language is interesting.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAlthough proficiency in a language may be the ability to both understand and convey ideas in that language, the former seems much more easier than the latter. Even in one's native language, it's fairly easy to understand what someone else is saying, but sometimes it can be difficult to convey your own thoughts, even though you've been speaking the language your whole life! I think the interesting part about this is when we think about speaking a language, we think mainly about just the verbal aspect. That is, how does one transform a sentence from one language and speak it in another language. As a result of this reliance on the verbal aspect, if you don't know the exact word or the right conjugation, you may not be able to effectively communicate what you are thinking.%0aConversely, when we imagine understanding someone speaking a different language, there are a number of other ways of getting information: facial expressions, gestures, etc. As a result, someone learning a new language can understand far more than they can speak. If you are at a dinner table and someone speaks a language you have never even heard of before but they point to a salt shaker next to you as they do it, you can probably understand that they asked you to pass the salt. It is examples like these of common situations everyone has been in that are the easiest to understand. These sort of common human situations lead to an almost universal language that exists outside of the verbal realm entirely, which can be very helpful to anyone trying to pick up a new language.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:Section: :)%0a(:Category: PracticeCategory:)
